7.1.1 - W11SR07: Ineffective Patch Management for Stand-alone Workstations
ISM controls:
•	1144; 1145; 1146 (Relating to the timely application of security patches for operating systems and applications).
•	1410; 1471 (Relating to system configuration management and software update processes).
•	1494 (Relating to the identification of security vulnerabilities in software).
Current Risk
The inability to manage and observe stand-alone workstations leads to significant configuration drift and the failure to apply critical security updates. There is a risk that OS and application patch management will be ineffectively executed for these disconnected assets, leaving known vulnerabilities unaddressed and resulting in an increased likelihood of system compromise and unauthorised data access.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	HIGH
Recommendations:
•	Establish an Offline Patching Lifecycle: Implement a formalised, recurring process for the manual ingestion and deployment of Microsoft Cumulative Updates and third-party application patches to all stand-alone workstations.
•	Vulnerability Scanning via Portable Media: Utilise approved portable scanning tools to periodically assess the vulnerability status of stand-alone devices, ensuring they meet the agency's mandatory patching timelines (e.g., 48-hour or 14-day requirements).
•	Centralised Asset Compliance Register: Maintain a high-fidelity register of the exact build numbers and patch levels of all stand-alone assets to facilitate reporting and risk oversight.
- Treatment #1
•	Develop a secure "clean-room" or "bridge" environment for downloading and verifying the integrity of update files before they are transferred to the stand-alone environment.
•	Implement scripted update deployments (e.g., via PowerShell) to ensure patches are applied consistently and that success/failure logs are captured for audit.
•	Mandatory decommissioning or isolation of any stand-alone workstation that cannot be patched within the timeframe specified in the ISM or departmental policy.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
While patching stand-alone systems remains a manual and resource-intensive task, the implementation of a structured, verified offline update process significantly mitigates the risk of unpatched vulnerabilities. By providing a clear mechanism for vulnerability identification and remediation, the likelihood of a compromise is reduced to "Unlikely."
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
UNLIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	MEDIUM

